{{multiple issues| {{close paraphrasing|date=July 2016}} {{third-party|date=July 2016}} }} {{distinguish|Intel Science Talent Search}}
The '''Intel International Science and Engineering Fair''' ('''Intel ISEF''') is a [[science fair]] and the largest pre-college scientific research event in the world,<ref>{{cite web|title=Intel International Science and Engineering Fair|url=http://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/education/competitions/international-science-and-engineering-fair.html|publisher=Intel|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref> and is owned and administered by the [[Society for Science & the Public]]<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://student.societyforscience.org/about|publisher=Society for Science and the Public|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref> a [[501(c)(3)]] [[non-profit organization]] based in Washington, DC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission and History|url=https://www.societyforscience.org/mission-and-history|publisher=Society for Science and the Public|accessdate=18 May 2014}}</ref> Each May, more than 1500 students from roughly 70 countries and territories compete in the fair for scholarships, tuition [[Grant (money)|grants]], [[internships]], scientific field trips and the grand prizes, including one $75,000 and two $50,000 [[college scholarship]]s. All prizes together amount to over $4,070,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAQ about the Intel ISEF|url=http://www.societyforscience.org/page.aspx?pid=276|publisher=Society For Science & the Public|accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref> Two awards ceremonies are held including: Special Awards Organization Presentation (which now includes the Government Awards Presentations) and the Grand Awards Ceremony. The International Science and Engineering Fair was founded in 1950 by [[Science Service]] (now the Society for Science & the Public) and has been sponsored by the [[Intel Corporation]] since 1997. As of 2012, seven ISEF alumni went on to win [[Nobel Prize]]s, with successful ISEF veterans including Jack Andraka and inventor [[Alex Deans]].<ref>http://www.societyforscience.org/alumni</ref>{{Failed verification|date=November 2018}}
== Location ==
Although it is an international event, the [[United States]] almost always hosts it (the 1995 fair was held [[Hamilton, Ontario]], [[Canada]]). Locations for fairs through 2020 have been decided: {{Div col|colwidth=24em}} * 2005: [[Phoenix, Arizona]], May 8–14. * 2006: [[Indianapolis, Indiana]], May 7–12. * 2007: [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], May 13–19. * 2008: [[Atlanta, Georgia]], May 11–17. * 2009: [[Reno, Nevada]], May 10–15. * 2010: [[San Jose, California]], May 9–14. * 2011: [[Los Angeles, California]], May 8–13. * 2012: [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], May 13–18. * 2013: [[Phoenix, Arizona]], May 12–17. * 2014: [[Los Angeles, California]], May 11–16. * 2015: [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], May 10-15. * 2016: [[Phoenix, Arizona]], May 8-13. * 2017: [[Los Angeles, California]], May 14-19. * 2018: [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], May 13-19. * 2019: [[Phoenix, Arizona]], May 12-17. * 2020: [[Anaheim, California]], May 13-18.<ref>https://student.societyforscience.org/intel-isef</ref> {{Div col end}}
== Contestants and competition ==
Contestants are selected from regional, district, and state ISEF affiliated fairs. These fairs usually encompass multiple states or entire regions of a country. The regional fair committee is responsible for managing the fair when their city hosts the event.
Individual science projects and team science projects both compete for prizes. Teams are composed of two to as many as four high school students (grades 9-12).
The structure of the competition is as follows: * Sunday: Arrival, project setup, fixing Display and Safety violations, and pin exchange * Monday: Continual arrival and setup, opening ceremony * Tuesday: Final project clearance * Wednesday: Awards judging over 3 sessions, with both scheduled and unscheduled interviews * Thursday: Public visitation day, special awards ceremony * Friday: Grand awards ceremony, project teardown
Additionally, time is set aside for students to experience the host city, with ISEF coordinating signups for various tours and activities. A significant component of the program is social, as students interact with each other during mixers and ceremonies. Throughout much of the week, various seminars are also held for students, mentors, and teachers.
== Prizes == {{Redirect|International Excellence in Teaching Award|the award given by University of Southampton Students' Union}} * [[Gordon E. Moore]] Award: $75,000 scholarship, given to the top of the Best of Category Award winners, selected on the basis of innovative research and potential of the project to have an impact in the particular field and the world as a whole. * Intel Foundation Young Scientist Award: $ 50,000 award presented by Intel and SSP to two Best in Category projects. Previous winners include [[Henry Lin (astronomer)|Henry Lin]] and [[Eesha Khare]]. * [[Dudley R. Herschbach]] SIYSS Award: all expense trip paid trip to the [[Stockholm International Youth Science Seminar]], and attendance to the [[Nobel Prize]] ceremonies. * [[European Union Contest for Young Scientists]]: All expense paid trip to European Union Contest. *Intel Best of Category Awards: Category winners are awarded a $5,000 scholarship; their school and the fair they represent are awarded a $1,000 grant.<ref>Intel ISEF grand awards. (n.d.). Retrieved December 12, 2012, from http://societyforscience.org/isef/grandawards</ref> * The [[Intel ISEF Finalist Medal]] is given to about 1800 student participants at the fair each year. * Intel ''International Excellence in Teaching Award'' is also given during the Intel ISEF since 1997. A prominent awardee was [[Josette Biyo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Small planet named after Pinoy science teacher |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/193829/small-planet-named-after-pinoy-science-teacher |accessdate=24 April 2017}}</ref>
ISEF also used to hold a "People's Choice Award" to allow the public to vote for its favorite entries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inspiredbyeducation.com/vote|title=Intel ISEF People's Choice Awards|accessdate=July 12, 2009|publisher=Intel ISEF}}</ref>
== Regeneron (formerly Intel and Westinghouse) Science Talent Search == {{Main|Regeneron Science Talent Search}} The [[Intel Science Talent Search|Regeneron (formerly Intel and Westinghouse) Science Talent Search]] is a related but separate science research competition for high school seniors studying in the United States that in previous years was also sponsored and named after [[Intel|Intel Corporation]]. Begun in 1942 as a partnership with [[Westinghouse Electric Corporation|Westinghouse]], then in 1998 with [[Intel]], and then in 2016 with [[Regeneron]], the [[Society for Science & the Public|Society for Science and the Public]] selects 40 contestants annually to present each's original research to the general public and members of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences|National Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.societyforscience.org/sts/|title=Intel Science Talent Search|accessdate=November 19, 2009|publisher=Society for Science and the Public}}</ref>
