{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}
{{Use South African English|date=September 2012}}
'''Lindsay Atkins Eddie''' (1845 &ndash; 13 October 1913) was a [[South Africa|South-African]] amateur [[astronomer]]. The son of an Army surgeon, Eddie also saw active military service, serving with distinction during the [[Kafir invasion]] in 1876. His final rank was that of a [[Major]].

During his career he observed 21 [[comet]]s, mostly from [[Grahamstown, South Africa]]. He observed a transit of [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] in 1894. In 1907 he studied the [[planet]] [[Mars]] with great detail and published drawings that were highly acclaimed.

He was an elected fellow of the [[Royal Astronomical Society]]. A [[Eddie (crater)|crater]] on Mars is named in his honor.

