{{Infobox scientist | name = Sue Biggins | image = | caption = | birth_date = 1968 | birth_place = | residence = [[United States]] | nationality = American | field = [[Cell biology]] | work_institutions = [[Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center]], [[University of Washington]] | alma_mater = [[Stanford University]], [[Princeton University]] | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | known_for = | prizes = [[American Academy of Arts & Sciences]] | footnotes = | website = }}
'''Sue Biggins''' (born 1968) is an American cell biologist who studies [[kinetochore]]s and the transfer of [[chromosomes]] during [[cell division]]. Her team isolated kinetochores from cells, enabling them to be studied separately under laboratory conditions. They also discovered that tension helps kinetochores to attach to microtubules and move from the mother cell to the daughter cells when cells divide. The methodology and concepts she developed for yeast kinetochores are being adopted in laboratories around the world. Biggins was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts & Sciences]] (AAAS) in 2018.<ref name="AAAS">{{cite news |last1=Tompa |first1=Rachel |title=Dr. Sue Biggins elected to American Academy of Arts & Sciences |url=https://www.fredhutch.org/en/news/center-news/2018/04/biggins-elected-american-academy-arts-sciences.html |accessdate=2 August 2018 |work=Fred Hutch News Service |date=April 18, 2018}}</ref>
==Education== Biggins received her [[Bachelor of Science|BS]] in biology in 1990 from [[Stanford University]] and her Ph.D. in Molecular Biology in 1995 at [[Princeton University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Susan Biggins |url=https://academictree.org/chemistry/peopleinfo.php?pid=77065 |website=Chemistry Tree |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sue Biggins |url=https://sharedresources.fredhutch.org/profile/biggins-sue |website=Fred Hutch Shared Rescources |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>
==Career== Biggins is currently the associate director and a full member of the basic sciences division at [[Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Faculty & Labs |url=http://www.fredhutch.org/en/labs/basic-sciences/faculty-labs.html |website=Basic Sciences Division |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> as well as an affiliate professor for the department of biochemistry at the [[University of Washington]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Faculty |url=http://www.pathology.washington.edu/academics/mmtp/biggins-sue/ |website=University of Washington Molecular Medicine & Mechanisms of Disease |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>
She was elected to the [[National Academy of Sciences]] in 2015<ref name="NAS2015">{{cite web |title=National Academy of Sciences, Member Directory |url=http://www.nasonline.org/member-directory/members/20035997.html |website=National Academy of Sciences |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> and to the [[American Academy of Arts & Sciences]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Fellows and International Honorary Members with their Affiliations at the Time of Election |url=https://www.amacad.org/content/members/newFellows.aspx?s=a |website=American Academy of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> She received the [[NAS Award in Molecular Biology|National Academy of Sciences Award in Molecular Biology]] in 2013.<ref name="NAS2013">{{cite news |title=National Academy of Sciences honors geneticist Sue Biggins |url=http://www.fredhutch.org/en/news/releases/2013/01/national-academy-sciences-honors-sue-biggins.html |accessdate=2 August 2018 |work=F |date=January 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sue Biggins receives the National Academy of Sciences Award in Molecular Biology |url=http://depts.washington.edu/sacklers/sue-biggins-receives-the-national-academy-of-sciences-award-in-molecular-biology/ |website=The Raymond and Beverly Sackler Scholars Program in Integrative Biophysics at the University of Washington |accessdate=2 August 2018|date= July 30, 2013}}</ref>
Biggins has also received a [[Beckman Young Investigators Award]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sue Biggins |url=http://www.beckman-foundation.org/beckman-young-investigators/sue-biggins |website=The Arnold and Mabel Beckman Foundation |accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> Biggins is also a [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]] Investigator.<ref name="Tompa">{{cite news |last1=Tompa |first1=Rachel |title='Every day something new': Dr. Sue Biggins selected as HHMI investigator |url=https://www.fredhutch.org/en/news/center-news/2015/05/sue-biggins-named-hhmi-investigator.html |accessdate=1 August 2018 |work=Fred Hutch News Service |date=May 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our Scientists |url=https://www.hhmi.org/scientists/sue-biggins |website=Howard Hughes Medical Institute |accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref> She was awarded the [[Edward Novitski Prize|Novitski Prize]] of the [[Genetics Society of America]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fred Hutch researcher Sue Biggins awarded the Genetics Society of America’s Novitski Prize |url=https://www.fredhutch.org/en/news/releases/2015/01/fred-hutch-researcher-sue-biggins-awarded-novitski-prize.html |accessdate=1 August 2018 |work=Fred Hutch News Service |date=January 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Edward Novitski Prize |url=http://www.genetics-gsa.org/awards/novitskiaward.shtml |website=Genetics Society of America |accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=HHMI>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhmi.org/scientists/sue-biggins|title=Sue Biggins, PhD - HHMI.org|publisher=}}</ref>
